summary:
The Security Council:
Reaffirms previous resolutions on Afghanistan, particularly resolution 1401 (2002) establishing UNAMA;
Reaffirms commitment to Afghanistan's sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity, and national unity;
Recognizes the Transitional Administration as the sole legitimate government pending democratic elections;
Decides to extend UNAMA for 12 months;
Welcomes the Secretary-General's report and endorses the proposal to establish an electoral unit within UNAMA;
Urges donors to coordinate with the Special Representative and Transitional Administration for recovery and reconstruction assistance;
Stresses that humanitarian assistance should be provided based on need, while recovery and reconstruction assistance should be provided through the Transitional Administration where local authorities demonstrate commitment to security, human rights, and countering narcotics;
Reaffirms support for the Special Representative and a fully integrated mission;
Requests UNAMA to assist the Afghan Independent Human Rights Commission;
Calls on Afghan parties to cooperate with UNAMA and ensure staff security;
Requests the International Security Assistance Force to work in close consultation with the Secretary-General and his Special Representative;
Requests the Secretary-General to report to the Council every four months;
Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
